passages.text: Quiet Week Ahead; Happy Labor Day!
Upcoming Week Highlights - This upcoming week is quiet from both a company and industry standpoint.
Further Out - The week of 9/8 features July PPI & CPI.
Past Week Highlights - This past week featured July new home sales down \(1\%\) (Street: flat) and July pending home sales roughly flat (Street: flat).
Stock Performance - Homebuilders rose \(4\%\) this week (Thurs- end), above the S&P's \(2\%\) rise and following last week's \(3\%\) decline (S&P: \(- 2\%\) ). Building Products rose \(3\%\) .

We maintain our more cautious stance on the homebuilders. We continue to take a more cautious, less constructive approach towards the homebuilders, as we anticipate a significantly less supportive demand/supply industry backdrop, while the builders' fundamentals will likely feature margin and ROE contraction during the upcoming year, and lastly, valuations remain full, in our view. Our Overweight- rated builders, which feature attractive relative valuations compared to our relative fundamental outlooks, include larger- cap PHM and smaller- cap TMHC. By contrast, we maintain a more optimistic and positive stance on our building products names for 2025, as we expect some improvement in both existing home sales and repair/remodel demand, alongside we believe reasonable valuations offering a favorable risk/reward. Our Overweight- rated building products names include BLD and MHK; by contrast, we rate SWK Underweight.

On Wednesday (8/27), the MBA Purchase Index rose \(2.2\%\) vs. last week to 163.8, while the 4- week moving average rose \(1.3\%\) versus last week to 160.6. The Refinance Index fell \(3.5\%\) versus last week to 894.1, bringing the 4- week moving average to 888.5, up \(4.6\%\) versus last week. Mortgage rates were mixed this week, with the 30- year mortgage rate up 1 bps to \(6.69\%\) , while the 5/1 ARM fell 7 bps to \(5.94\%\) . ARM's market share fell 20 bps to \(8.4\%\) .
The 10- year Treasury fell 13 bps to \(4.2\%\) .
This past week featured July new home sales down \(1\%\) (Street: flat) and July pending home sales roughly flat (Street: flat).
This past week was quiet from a company perspective.

The July Pending Home Sales Index - which represents homes entered into contract, not closings - fell \(0.4\%\) sequentially to 71.7, roughly in- line with the Street's outlook for a \(0.2\%\) decline to 71.8. Additionally, on a YOY basis, July pending home sales rose \(0.7\%\) which follows last month's \(2.8\%\) decline. Other recent housing data points also reflect similar trends, including the August NAHB survey down 1 points seq. and \(18\%\) YOY, July existing home sales up \(2\%\) seq. and \(1\%\) YOY, July new home sales down \(1\%\) seq. and \(8\%\) YOY and July housing starts up \(5\%\) seq. and \(13\%\) YOY.

July new home sales fell \(0.6\%\) sequentially to 652K, though above the Street's outlook for a \(0.5\%\) rise to 630K (prior month revised up to 656K from 627K). On a YOY basis, July fell \(8.2\%\) , which follows June's \(2.2\%\) fall and May's \(5.3\%\) fall. Importantly, we continue to view data points for this metric as fairly volatile on a month- to- month basis, and hence note that on a 3- month moving average basis, new home sales are averaging 646K, down \(5.3\%\) YOY. Other recent housing data points also reflect similar trends, including the August NAHB survey down 1 points seq. and \(18\%\) YOY, July existing home sales up \(2\%\) seq. and \(1\%\) YOY and July housing starts up \(5\%\) seq. and \(13\%\) YOY.
We did not publish any building products research on this week.
